🎓 PART 1: BIG PICTURE (say this first)

👉 Tell students:

“We have 2 main files:

MCP server → handles tools and routing
order_service.py → does real work (AWS + Claude + DB)”
🧠 PART 2: ARCHITECTURE (draw this first)
Frontend / AI
     ↓
mcp.py (TOOL LAYER)
     ↓
order_service.py (LOGIC LAYER)
     ↓
AWS + Claude AI
📦 FILE 1: mcp.py (TOOL SERVER)
🔹 LINE 1–10: Imports

👉 What to say:

“We import Flask, system tools, and order_service functions.”

Important:

from order_service import place_order, get_order, customer_answer

✔ This means MCP does NOT do logic
✔ It only uses functions from order_service

🔹 LINE 12–60: TOOLS LIST
TOOLS = [...]

👉 Explain:

“This is a list of all actions AI or frontend can call.”

Example:
place_order 🍔
get_order 📦
get_order_status 📊
summarize_order 🧾
answer_customer_query 🤖

✔ Think of it like a MENU in restaurant

🔹 LINE 62–110: read_message()

👉 Explain simply:

“This is for communication between AI and MCP server using stdio.”

✔ Reads request
✔ Parses JSON
✔ Returns message

🔹 LINE 112–135: send_message / response

👉 Explain:

“This sends response back to UI or AI.”

🔹 LINE 140: handle_tool_call (MOST IMPORTANT 🔥)

This is the HEART ❤️

🟢 TOOL: place_order
if tool_name == "place_order":
LINE 142–150:
payload = dict(arguments or {})

👉 copy input from user

LINE 151–153:
if "item" not in payload

👉 validation

✔ item is required
✔ prevents bad input

LINE 154:
payload["quantity"] = int(payload["quantity"])

👉 convert string → number

🚨 LINE 155 (IMPORTANT LINE)
data, status_code = place_order(payload)

👉 SAY THIS TO STUDENTS:

“THIS is where MCP calls backend logic (order_service.py)”

✔ NOT AWS yet
✔ Just Python function call

LINE 156–160:
return text_result(...)

👉 returns response to user

📦 FILE 2: order_service.py (REAL WORK FILE)
🔹 LINE 1–20: Imports + config

👉 Explain:

“This file connects to AWS + Claude AI”

Important:

boto3.resource("dynamodb")

✔ connects to DynamoDB

🔹 LINE 25–40: get_order()
table.get_item(Key={"orderId": order_id})

👉 THIS is AWS call

✔ reads DynamoDB
✔ returns order data

🔹 LINE 42–55: build_summary()

👉 simple formatting function

✔ converts order → human text

🔹 LINE 60–90: ask_claude()

👉 Explain:

“This sends order data to Claude AI for smart answers”

LINE 70:
urlrequest.Request(CLAUDE_MESSAGES_URL)

👉 THIS is API call to:

Anthropic

✔ sends prompt
✔ gets AI response

🔹 LINE 95–110: place_order()

👉 VERY IMPORTANT 🔥

LINE 100:
urlrequest.Request(ORDER_API_URL)

👉 THIS is AWS API Gateway call

✔ sends order to backend system

FLOW after this:
API Gateway → Lambda → SQS → DynamoDB
🔹 LINE 120–135: customer_answer()
order = get_order(order_id)

👉 Step 1: get data from DynamoDB

ask_claude(order, question)

👉 Step 2: send to AI (Claude)

🧠 FINAL FLOW (VERY IMPORTANT FOR STUDENTS)
🟢 Place Order Flow
User
 ↓
mcp.py (handle_tool_call)
 ↓
order_service.place_order()
 ↓
API Gateway
 ↓
Lambda
 ↓
SQS
 ↓
DynamoDB
🟡 Get Order Flow
User
 ↓
mcp.py
 ↓
order_service.get_order()
 ↓
DynamoDB
🤖 Ask Question Flow
User question
 ↓
mcp.py
 ↓
order_service.customer_answer()
 ↓
DynamoDB + Claude AI
🧾 SIMPLE EXPLANATION FOR STUDENTS

You can literally say:

“MCP is like a receptionist that receives requests.
order_service is the kitchen that does real work.
AWS is the backend system that stores and processes data.
Claude AI is the smart assistant that generates answers.”

🎯 ONE-LINE SUMMARY (for exam)

MCP server exposes tools and routes requests, while order_service handles actual business logic including AWS operations and Claude AI integration.
